   Planned Parenthood v. American Coalition of Life Activists, 99-35320 /
   99-35325 / 99-35327 / 99-35331 / 99-35333 / 99-35405
   Three-Judge Panel Opinion: 244 F.3d 1007 (9th Cir. 2001)
   Order Taking Case En Banc: 268 F.3d 908 (9th Cir. 2001)
   Date of Order Taking Case En Banc: October 3, 2001
   Status: Argued and submitted December 11, 2001, 2:00 p.m., Pasadena
   Members of En Banc Court: Mary M. Schroeder, Stephen R. Reinhardt, Alex
   Kozinski, Diarmuid F. O'Scannlain, Pamela A. Rymer, Andrew J.
   Kleinfeld, Michael D. Hawkins, Barry G. Silverman, Kim M. Wardlaw,
   Marsha S. Berzon, Johnnie B. Rawlinson.
   Issue(s): Did actions by American Coalition of Life Activists,
   including speech, "wanted"-style posters identifying abortion-providing
   physicians and list of physicians on their Internet website violate the
   Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act? Were the actions protected
   political speech under the First Amendment because they could not be
   construed as direct threats of harm to providers who did not stop
   performing abortions?
   Holding: Not yet decided
     __________________________________________________________________

   United States v. Buckland, 99-30285
   Three-Judge Panel Opinion: 259 F.3d 1157 (9th Cir. 2001)
   Order Taking Case En Banc: 265 F.3d 1085 (9th Cir. 2001)
   Date of Order Taking Case En Banc: September 14, 2001
   Status: Affirmed criminal sentence
   En Banc Opinion: 2002 WL 63718 (9th Cir. Jan. 18, 2002)
   Date of En Banc Opinion: January 18, 2002
   Members of En Banc Court: Mary M. Schroeder, Procter R. Hug, Stephen R.
   Reinhardt, Diarmuid F. O'Scannlain, Stephen S. Trott, Thomas G. Nelson,
   Andrew J. Kleinfeld, A. W. Tashima, Ronald M. Gould, Richard A. Paez,
   Richard C. Tallman.
   Issue(s): Are 21 U.S.C. §§ 841(b)(1)(A) and (B) facially
   unconstitutional under Apprendi v. New Jersey, 530 U.S. 466 (2000),
   because they permit the judge to find under the preponderance of the
   evidence standard a fact, the quantity of drugs, that increases the
   maximum penalty to which a defendant is exposed?
   Holding(s): Apprendi does not render 21 U.S.C. § 841(b) facially
   unconstitutional, and Ninth Circuit case law, including United States
   v. Nordby, 225 F.3d 1053 (9th Cir. 2000), is overruled to the extent it
   is inconsistent or holds to the contrary. The panel held that the
   judge's Apprendi error, determining drug quantity which increased the
   maximum sentence to which Buckland was exposed, was harmless.
